    public interface ITagValues
extends ITagValuesReadable, IFIXBytesImportable
    Collection of ITagValue objects.

    Multiple ITagValue's can exist with the same tag number. They will have an implied ordering.

    Note that there are no explicit methods for getting/setting/adding double values. You should use the corresponding Decimal methods instead. Note also that you can perform arithmetic directly on Decimal objects using the methods Decimal.add(Decimal), Decimal.subtract(Decimal), Decimal.multiply(Decimal) and Decimal.divide(Decimal,int). So conversion to double (which is expensive and introduces precision issues) may not be necessary at all.

    Method Summary:

    • Inherits all the ITagValuesReadable methods - see summary for ITagValuesReadable
    • addField(ITagValue)
    • addField( int tag, X ) where X = BytesSegment, Decimal, int, long, String
    • addFieldAsX( int tag, Y ) and setValueAsX( int tag, Y ) where X = AsciiBytes, UnicodeBytes and Y = byte[], BytesSegment
    • clearTagValues()
    • copyFrom(ITagValues)
    • getFreeTagValue()
    • addTagValuesListener(ITagValuesListener) and removeTagValuesListener(ITagValuesListener)
    • removeField(int)
    • setValue(int, IValue)
    • setValue( int tag, X ) where X = IValue, byte[], BytesSegment, Decimal, int, long, String

      • addField

        void addField(ITagValue field)
        Add the given field to the end of the list of fields.

        Note that ITagValue objects may be reused across multiple method invocations by ITagValues implementations. If you retrieved the 'field' object from a different ITagValues you should make a copy and pass the copy into this method.

        Alternatively, you can use addField(int, IValue) which does exactly that, e.g. addField(field.getTag(), field.getValue()).

        Parameters:
        field - Field to be added.

      • addFieldAt

        void addFieldAt(int index,
                ITagValue field)
        Inserts the specified ITagValue at the specified position in the list of fields. Shifts the element currently at that position (if any) and any subsequent ITagValue to the right (adds one to their indices).

        This method is optional. Not all implementations support indexed operations.

        Parameters:
        index - Index at which the specified field is to be inserted
        field - Field to be inserted
        Throws:
        UnsupportedOperationException - if the underlying implementation does not support indexed operations
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the index is out of range (index < 0 || index > size())

      • clearTagValues

        void clearTagValues()
        Clears out any existing message content - leaving an empty message, ie a message with no fields.

        Note that a message implementation that supports reuse may move the existing fields into a free pool for future reuse - for example, through the getFreeTagValue() method.

      • copyFrom

        void copyFrom(ITagValues other)
        Replaces the current fields with the supplied ITagValues. Unlike ITagValuesReadable.clone(), which clones everything, undefined/reusable fields in 'other' are not copied.

        If other is null, does nothing.

        Parameters:
        other - ITagValues whose fields are to be copied. May be null.
        See Also:
        IValue.isUndefined()

      • appendFrom

        void appendFrom(ITagValues other)
        Adds all of the supplied fields to this object, creating additional fields with the same tags where a field already exists.

        If other is null, does nothing.

        Parameters:
        other - ITagValues whose fields are to be appended to this object. May be null.

      • getFreeTagValue

        ITagValue getFreeTagValue()
        Returns a free tag value object, creating one if necessary.

        This is a better way of getting ITagValue objects than creating them yourself using new. This method allows tag value field reuse in reused messages. The idea is that when clearTagValues() is called on an ITagValues, any ITagValue objects are not discarded, but instead are saved and used as a "free pool", accessible through this method.

        The IValue part of the returned tag value must not be null.

        Returns:
        ITagValue object

      • removeFieldAt

        boolean removeFieldAt(int index)
        Removes the ITagValue at the specified position in the list of fields. Shifts any subsequent elements to the left (subtracts one from their indices).

        This method is optional. Not all implementations support indexed operations.

        Parameters:
        index - the index of the element to be removed
        Returns:
        true if field was removed
        Throws:
        UnsupportedOperationException - if the underlying implementation does not support indexed operations
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the index is out of range (index < 0 || index >= size())

      • removeAllFields

        void removeAllFields(BitSet tagsToRemove)
        Removes all instances of the specified fields.

        This method is a more efficient alternative to removeAllFields(int), which must be called repeatedly for each tag.

        Parameters:
        tagsToRemove - A BitSet that defines the tags to remove. The bit index corresponds to a specific tag number; setting a bit to true indicates that the tag should be removed if present in the message. It is recommended that the caller does not create a new set for each call, in order to eliminate garbage creation.

      • setFieldValue

        void setFieldValue(int tag,
                   IValue value)
        Sets the value of the first tag/value field with the given tag.

        If no such entry exists it is created.

        If the entry already exists, its value is updated.

        If value is null, the entry is removed if present.

        Note that IValue objects may be reused across multiple method invocations so the internal implementation should NOT store a reference to the IValue object passed in. It should copy its contents.

        Parameters:
        tag - Tag number.
        value - New value for entry.
